column168: At approximately 1220 hours on June 1, 2014 when the train crew in Mingo Yard was switching, they noticed an odor coming from PROX 44520.  Lorne Dodds, Road Foreman for the Wheeling and Lake Erie called Rail Loading Services in Rayland Ohio, who loaded this car, to come up and take a look to see what the problem was.  Shane Yarnevic from RLS came to Mingo at about 1300hrs. to take a look.  He found that the manway on this car had loose manway bolts.  He tightened the bolts, securing the car and then released the car for service.  He stated that they were at fault for the loose bolts.

column25: UPS SUPPLY CHAIN SOLUTIONS ON BEHALF OF PHILADELPHIA CYCLE CENTER
column168: SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY EMIRATES AS A CONSOLIDATION UNDER A MASTER AIR WAYBILL AND ONE HOUSE WAYBILL ON MAY 21ST 2014.  AFTER TENDERING TO EMIRATES, THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED ON HOLD BY THE FREIGHT FORWARDER (UPS SUPPLY CHAIN SOLUTIONS), IN ORDER TO COMPLETE US CUSTOMS CLEARANCE REQUIRED FOR VEHICLES. ONCE THE AUTHORIZATION FROM US CUSTOMS WAS SUBMITTED TO EMIRATES AND RELEASE FOR TRANSPORT WAS GIVEN, EMIRATES CONDUCTED SECURITY SCREENING OF THE PACKAGE ON JUNE 03RD 2014, WHICH RESULTED IN THE DISCOVERY OF A MOTORCYCLE ENCLOSED IN A CONTAINER AND INSIDE THE CONTAINER A SEPARATE CARTON MARKED AS "BATTERY FLUID, ACID (UN2796)".  EMIRATES WAS UNABLE TO CONFIRM IF MOTORCYCLE CONTAINED ANY FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS OR FUMES BECAUSE THE KEYS WERE NOT TENDERED WITH SHIPMENT AND GAS TANK WAS LOCKED. SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED AND UPS WAS TOLD TO RETRIEVE SHIPMENT FROM EMIRATES FACILITY.

column168: A driver was at a customer's site to pickup 4 totes of hazardous waste.  The last tote was sticking out of the rear of the truck and needed to be pushed in further.  Rather than take a pallet and carefully push the tote in, the forklift driver backed up against it and rammed it into the truck, the force causing the tote to split and leak out 10 gallons of liquid.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material with a suitable absorbent material.  The remaining material in the damaged tote was pumped back into the shipper's tank.
column169: The shipper was dealing with the employee who operated the forklift recklessly to use more caution when loading totes.

column168: on 06/04/2014 @ 2315ET hours, Scott Horton of Landstar-Ranger trucking contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions(ERTS) regarding a release of approximately 8 (eight) ounces of UN 3082 Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid N.O.S, from a leaking 330 gallon tote on flatbed trailer. ERTS made regulatory reporting to the ND Dept of Health and tracking # E14060400602 was issued by Operator 817. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor, USES of Dickinson, ND. to the scene to secure the site and conduct clean up operations. Prior to contractor arrival on scene, the driver placed a granular absorbent in the area of the leak to minimize product release. USES arrived on site and determined that there was a crack in a tote causing the minimal release of the product (approximately 16 ounces). USES performed a product transfer into 7 (seven) poly drums. The drums were properly labeled and subsequent clean up of the impacted area was performed. All wastes were collected, containerized and taken for proper disposal.

column168: Tank car UTLX 46741 in the railyard was reported with commodity staining on its side shell that emanating from its manway closure. UTLX 46741 was carefully moved and isolated on a repair track in the railyard. In the morning of 6/02/2014, contract responders inspecting UTLX 46741 reported the manway cover gasket out of its groove, pinched and damaged. The damaged gasket was removed and a new Nitrile manway nozzle gasket was installed. The manway closure was closed, properly secured and sealed. Also noted during inspection was the vapor valve in an open position with its closure cap secure. The vapor valve was closed. Flange stud bolt nuts on the liquid valve's mounting flange that were found less than tool tight were also tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Non-evaporated spillage on the side shell and around the manway nozzle was wiped There was no ground impact from the spillage. Intact shipper seals were replaced by TIS seal 5201 at the manway closure and TIS seal 5202 at the protective housing cover. Response was concluded by 1045 hrs. MDT, 6/02/2014.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A driver picked up a tanker load of recyclable ethyl alcohol and returned to the ten day storage yard.  When the lab personnel went out to sample the load, a small drip was noticed coming from the valve cap. He put a bucket under it and notified the proper persons.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and stopped the leak.  A gasket was found to be leaking and was replaced by the maintenance department.  The load then traveled to the intended disposal site without further incident.
column169: The driver did not notice any signs of leaking when he completed his post trip inspection.  The gasket was old and showed signs of deterioration.  The maintenance department will check the gaskets on the caps of all tankers in the local fleet.

column168: The driver was at the Floyd Parker oil well lease.  As part of their loading procedure the driver has to stop and take two samples to verify the water content in the oil is low enough.  Both samples came back above the authorized amount.  Driver was supposed to call in to his dispatcher when this happens.  He failed to do so.  Then the driver made the command decision to pump the oil back into the customer's tank.  At most well sites this wouldn't be an issue but at this location the tank happened to be a live production tank meaning it is continually filling.  As the driver pumped the oil from his trailer back into the customers tank the tank began overflowing.  Everything went into a containment area at this tank 'battery'.  USES was hired to come out and collect the contaminated soil in the containment area and clean the outside of the customer tank.
column169: This driver was fairly new to this type of business.  Driver has been shut down for future loads and is going to be spending time with one of our OSR's (Operations Safety Representatives) to go over the various sites and how they can differ, then reinforce our strict loading procedures and consequences if they aren't followed, and lastly a skills demonstration test to validate that the driver got the message and can perform the job tasks without incident.

column168: The cause of the damaged pails was due to inadequate blocking and bracing of other freight loaded around pails. column169: Training topics will continue to be covered with dock employees in regards to the importance of proper blocking and bracing techniques and procedures. This particular incident can be used as a learning tool when training employees on block and bracing.

column168: An ASO trailer was over filled during loading. The trailer was overloaded above capacity due to an error of the Shift Supervisor in calculating to amount to be loaded into the trailer. Upon filling the trailer it’s PSV (Pressure Safety Valve) opened and released 10 gallons (80 pounds) of ASO to the grade. The loading pump was immediately shut down and the inlet to the trailer blocked in. Absorbent was applied to the spill until all liquid was absorbed.  The excess in ASO the trailer was then pressured with N2 back to the D-901 drum until the trailer had 5” of vapor space above the liquid level. The loading line was then blown clear and the trailer disconnected. The trailer was then de-pressured and secured. The absorbent will be drummed and the trailer was cleaned before shipping.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: During offloading at the W Mifflin PA branch, the driver noticed liquid material coming from a drum on his truck. The driver placed absorbent pads along the bottom of the drum and called his supervisor. A response crew was summoned. Upon arrival, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the truck. It was found that the drum was leaking from the lower body. A suitable salvage drum was used for repackaging of the leaking drum and all of the absorbent material used to contain and clean the spill. The PA DEP was called and chose not to respond as the spill was immediatly attended to and cleaned.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver was reinstructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before shipping and acceptance for transportation;if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.The shipper was also notified to conduct inspections prior to loading for shipment.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: On 06/06/2013 at 12:20 hours, personnel on the CSXT Great Lakes Division discovered GATX21414, a residue tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the frangible disc as it was ruptured from overpressure. The car was isolated and shipper, PVS Chemical from Detroit, MI, were notified. CHEMTREC Report number was issued: 2014-06-06-00187. Summit Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disc ruptured from overpressure. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, PVS Chemical  313-924-2640. Contractor personnel fixed the problem and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured. The incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code:1004  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: UNDECLARED HAZMAT DISCOVERED WHILE MOVING NON HAZMAT MARKED PKG TO BELT. SOUNDS OF RATTLING CONTAINERS WITHIN PKG COULD BE HEARD. DURING FURTHER INSPECTION, 5 PRESSURIZED CONTAINERS WITH DOT-SP 10704 MARKED ON THEM DISCOVERED INSIDE PKG.
column169: SHIPPER FOLLOWUP.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: This shipment was discovered when a similar shipment from the same shipper to the CVS (different store) broke open and the contents were visible. It contained a display of suntan lotion which included aerosol cans which said flammable. As the shipment was not offered with any DG markings, labels nor with a shipper's declaration it's believed to be undeclared DG. FedEx held the shipment pending FAA investigation. FAA agent Joan Haas was notified.    THIS SHIPMENT BROKE OPEN DURING THE SORT. WHEN THE EMPLOYEE WENT TO RETAPE THE PACKAGE THEY SAW THE CONTENTS - SUNTAN LOTION BUT SEVERAL WERE AEROSOL CANS. THEY SAID HIGHLY FLAMMABLE ON THEM. AS THE SHIPPER HAD NOT OFFERED THE SHIPMENT WITH ANY DG MARKINGS, LABELS NOR WITH A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DG. THE SHIPMENT APPEARED TO BE FOR A DEPARTMENT STORE DISPLAY AND THE EMPLOYEE HAD SEEN SOME OTHER SHIPMENTS TO OTHER CVS STORES FROM THAT SHIPPER SO THEY SENT A MESSAGE TO ALL COURIERS AT THAT STATION TO HOLD ANY SHIPMENTS ON THEIR DELIVERY VEHICLES FROM THAT SHIPPER FOR POSSIBLE INSPECTION AS UNDECLARED DG. FIVE OTHER SHIPMENTS WERE DISCOVERED. ALL 6 SHIPMENTS WERE HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. SEPARATE 5800'S WILL BE DONE FOR EACH OF THE OTHER SHIPMENTS. FAA JOAN HAAS WAS NOTIFIED.
column169: I SPOKE WITH THE OPERATIONS MANAGER AT THE SHIPPER'S COMPANY. THEY HAD INADVERTENTLY SENT A MASS MAILING OF UNDECLARED DG NOT RECOGNIZING THE AEROSOL CANS AS DG/HAZMAT. I EXPLAINED THAT NO OTHER SHIPMENTS COULD GO. OUT OF THIS PRODUCT UNTIL EITHER THEY HAD DG TRAINING OR HIRED A DG PACK AND SHIP VENDOR TO PREPARE IT FOR THEM. THEY ALSO ASKED ABOUT GROUND REGULATIONS WHICH WOULD BE LESS RESTRICTIVE AND I DIRECTED THEM TO SOME COLLEAGUES AT FEDEX GROUND SAFETY FOR THEIR FUTURE SHIPMENTS. I ALSO MADE ONE OF THE LOCAL FEDEX MANAGERS WHO SUPPORTS THIS ACCOUNT AWARE OF THE ISSUE AS WELL AS THE FEDEX DISTRICT SALES MANAGER.

column42: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column168: Employee's forklift punctured the carton and one of the 1 gallon containers inside during loading. At 0355ET hours, Con-Way Freight Safety contacted ERTS (emergency response vendor) regarding a release of an unknown amount of UN1790 HYDROFLUORIC ACID to a trailer at the Con-Way Terminal in Albany NY. ERTS contacted terminal for more information and was advised that the release was to the trailer and was leaking to the ground adjacent to the trailer. No drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted at the time of the initial report. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor, TMC, with an ETA of 1 hour. ERTS notified NY Dept of Environmental Conservation on Con-way Freight's behalf and Operator # 33 issued tracking # 1402625.  Safety Manager was on scene by 0500.  Fire Department had evacuated terminal.  NRC contacted and tracking # 1085506 was issued. TMC advised that a pallet containing 9 boxes containing four 1-gallon containers per box was impacted. TMC advised the FD reported 1 gallon released. TMC containerized the absorbent in a cubic yard box for staging. Sodium Bicarbonate was used to neutralize the impacted areas. Material to be disposed of by waste disposal company.  Total cost of incident unknown at the time of reporting.

column168: A pallet of drums of hazardous waste was being loaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility onto a trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  To load the pallet onto the trailer, an empty pallet was being placed on end to push the loaded pallet onto the rear of the trailer.  A board broke on the pallet, causing the fork to pierce the drum.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The spilled material was cleaned up with a suitable cleaning compound and placed into the salvage drum.  The shipment then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The persons loading the shipment were advised to discontinue this practice immediately and load trailers properly--using more care.

column62: Valve Open; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF switchman reported tank car GROX 132050 in the railyard leaking commodity from its top fitting area. Immediate inspection of GROX 132050 by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders revealed the liquid valve was in an open position with its camlock closure cap loose (not secured). The responders closed the liquid valve and secured its camlock closure cap by 1245 hrs. PDT, 6/04/2014 which ended any further commodity release from this fitting.    Contract responders were called-in for ground spill remediation and these responders reported over 2000 linear feet of stained ballast in the yard track from GROX 132050's commodity release while it was in motion. Impacted ballast and soils were excavated and the excavated site was treated with microbial bio-stimulate to remediate any remaining traces of spilled commodity. The excavation site was backfilled with native soils and topped with clean ballast. On 6/05/2014, contract responders degreased and pressure washed all spillage from GROX 132050. Excavated materials and cleaning rinsate were earmarked for appropriated disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On June 9, 2014 at approximately 17:00 FRA HazMat inspectors working in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered UTLX 660603, a residue tank car of environmentally hazardous substance liquid N.O.S leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and shipper Koppers Erin Murray 412-298-8497, was notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014-06-09-00199. SPSI a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the BOV was leaking. SPSI cycled the valve and the release stopped. Contractor personnel and cleaned up spilled material. The FRA HazMat inspector notified Koppers and CSX that an OTMA-3 was needed for the car. Koppers, Erin Murray was applying for the OTMA. The car was on an outbound train and by the time it was communicated to hold the car it was moved in a train to Connellsville, Pa. CSXT Hazmat had the car set out and FRA notified of same.   This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident does not require a 7.1    NARRI =707  5X(4+1+0)X(2+0)=50
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: On June 11th, 2014 at 10:06 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered TCBX 193308, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car, coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Musket Corporation, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-06-11-00101. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that manway cover swing bolts #3 + #4 to be less than tool tight, causing a release of product between the manway cover gasket and the nozzle, the gasket was inspected, wipe down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened.  Mr. Thad Davis, Musket Corp. Rail Logistics Manager, Office: 405-302-6582 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. TCBX 193308 was released for transport.    This incident did require a special move.    Cause Code: 200 (5 points)  NARRI: 5x(5+5+0)x(2+0) = 100
column169: Notified Shipper; Musket Corporation that loaders should review AAR Pamphlet 34, for proper handling and securement of tank cars prior to offering for transportation.

A BNSF mechanical car inspector reported entrained tank car GAMX 6537 arriving on an inbound BNSF train in the railyard leaking commodity from its top fitting area. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected GAMX 6537 and observed liquid commodity intermittently being expelled from GAMX 6537's reclosing pressure relief valve (which is indicative of a volume overfill condition). GAMX 6537 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with containment placed under GAMX 6537 while awaiting commodity reduction. Contract responders removed approximately 1500 gallons from GAMX 6537 into a tanker truck for ultimate delivery to the consignee. Also included in that scheduled delivery was the spilled commodity captured in the containment receptacle that was placed under GAMX 6537. Measured commodity outage in GAMX 6537 was 2 inches before commodity reduction and 10 inches after the commodity reduction. After the reduction, no further commodity release was observed from the pressure relief valve. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The spillage on GAMX 6537 was wiped, degreased and pressure washed. Observed ground spillage was excavated and the excavation site was treated with microbial bio-stimulate to remediate any remaining traces of spilled commodity. The excavated site was backfilled with native soils and topped with clean ballast.  Excavated materials and cleaning rinsate were earmarked for appropriate disposal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings, including adherence to appropriate commodity outage levels.

column168: Vehicle was heading East, a large building was being transported going West on Highway 14 1 mile West of Briggsdale, Co. The drivers slowed almost to a stop pulling to right dirt shoulder of the road. It had rained the previous nights and the shoulder was soft. The shoulder caused the truck to sink on the passenger side, the angle of the right shoulder and the vehicle being top heavy caused the vehicle to become unbalanced a vehicle rolled 3/4 resting on diver side. Clamps were installed on dome lid that was showing slight leakage, but absorbent pads and floor dry was in place to capture the product. State Patrol and HazMat was on site, no ticket was issued. Clean up only had to take absorbants, pads, and catch basins for cleanup mitigation.
column169: Instruct driver to not use shoulder of road if not paved. Patrolman stated that the driver did everything possible to avoid a crash, and weather was main cause for condition of road shoulder.   We are purchasing dome clamps on units to use in case another emergency happens.

column168: On June 24, 2014, R&L Carriers contacted ERTS in regards to a UN3287 Toxic Liquid, inorganic release from what appeared to be unsecure bungs on 4 of the totes that were loaded on the trailer apparently on their side and the minimal amount in the empty totes was released to the trailer floor from the loose bungs. A contractor was dispatched and righted the totes and secured them. They then cleaned up the impacted trailer floor with absorbents.

A 55 (fifty-five) gallon drum fell off the back of a trailer after being loaded onto the rear of that trailer. Due to a tight loading area, the driver was pulling out of a dock in order to close the back doors of the trailer, when the drum fell from the rear of the trailer striking the ground. The drum ruptured and released  all of it contents to the parking lot below. Facility personnel immediately applied granular absorbents to the impacted areas. Facility personnel then contacted Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) of Solon, Ohio to manage the clean up operations. Facility personnel also contacted the local 911 system. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor for clean up operations and made the required regulatory reporting. The environmental contractor, the Northridge Group of New York responded and conducted clean up operations. All wastes were collected, containerized and taken from proper disposal. At this time, the wastes are being profiled and will we taken for proper disposal.

column168: THE UNLOADER IN DOOR 31 NOTICED A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE IN DOOR 31. HE LEFT THE TRAILER & NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR, WHO NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS OF THE LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I THEN CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TUB. AS I MOVED THE PACKAGE, IT BEGAN TO GIVE OFF A STRONG ODOR. MY PARTNER, RODNEY HAD JOINED ME BY THEN & WENT TO GET THE SCBA TO FINISH THE CLEANUP. RODNEY PH TESTED THE LIQUID THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID UNTIL THE PH WAS IN THE 6-9 RANGE. THEN HE USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID. HE SWEPT UP ALL MATERIALS USED IN CLEANUP & PUT IT IN ANOTHER LINED SPILL TUB. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED, I DISCOVERED THAT 1 GLASS BOTTLE CRACKED/SHATTERED.

column168: On 6/06/2014, a switching mishap in the railyard resulted in equipment damage to tank car SGAX 1068's B-end platform area. This damage sustained to SGAX 1068 necessitated transfer of the commodity within SGAX 1068 into another suitable tank car.   On 6/10/2014, the contract responders assigned to make this commodity transfer were engaged in a pre-transfer assessment of SGAX 1068 when they noticed a commodity odor emanating from SGAX 1068 and commodity staining around SGAX 1068's manway nozzle and on its side shell. Further inspection into SGAX 1068's manway securement revealed that the manway gasket was missing. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and SGAX 1068's manway closure was properly re-secured and sealed. Also, the liquid valve's closure plug was found less than tool tight with this valve in the closed position. The responders' tool tightened the liquid valve's closure plug. Intact shipper seals numbered 9700856 and 9700857 were replaced by seals numbered 872372 and 872378. The spillage on SGAX 1068 was cleaned.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A Veolia employee transported a shipment from Larimer County Landfill to the Veolia, Henderson facility.  Upon arrival, a small leak out onto the metal deck of truck was discovered. Upon further investigation the leaking drum was identified.  The cause of the leak was determined to be a deteriorated drum gasket the failed to form a proper seal between the drum and the lid.  It was not discovered during loading because the drum was placed on the truck with a forklift in the upright position.  The leaking drum was overpacked into the appropriate container and all other containers were inspected to ensure they were not leaking and were of good integrity.
column169: Customer will be contacted in order to ensure they properly inspect and offer non leaking drums for transportation.  Veolia employees will perform a more detailed visual inspection of the drum before accepting materials for transportation.  Awareness training will be given to Veolia employees to review the incident and what to watch for when shipping hazmat.

column168: On June 10th at 1640 hours FRA Inspector David Snyder discovered CSXT250030, a loaded hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate leaking product from a 2.5 x 3 corrosion crack on the right hand side corner of # 2 bottom chute / slope sheet.  The car was isolated and the shipper, PCS Sales was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-0610-00263.  PCS Sales dispatched an emergency response team to temporarily secure the container.  On June 17th, PCS Sales was granted a one-time movement approval FRA-14060461 to return the rail car back to their facility to be off loaded.  This incident did require a special switching move.    2(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24 NARRI

column168: On June 17, 2014, at 1322 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Parsons Yard, Columbus, Ohio noticed a slight drip from the bottom of SCMX 2484, a loaded tank car of UN3082, Environmentally Hazardous Material Liquids, NOS. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Shell Chemical Company , was notified via Chemtrec, report #2014-06-17-00222 . Environmental Management Specialists EMS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Parsons Yard. EMS the cap on the bottom outlet to be leaking. The cap was removed and a deteriorated gasket was replaced. The bottom outlet valve appeared to be properly holding and the release was residual material. The shipper representative, Rick Ferguson, (832) 712-9770 was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and SCMX 2484 was released for disposition.  This incident did not require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60  Cause code:580

Trailer was picked up from Veolia ES, Flanders, NJ brought to our 10 day facility.  A complaint of an odor was called in that night to the local police.  Police responded with Morris County Hazmat and Fire to locate specific cause of odor.  After odor was located this trailer, we were contacted and notified our customer Veolia ES who responded as Emergency Response Clean Up.  Trailer was taken to Veolia ES, Flanders, drum was overpacked and cleaned up.  Leak of approximately 3 gallons, located in our yard, was put into drums and taken to Veolia ES.  DEP and Morris County Hazmat oversaw all operations for clean up.
column169: Failure was due to over pressure in drum due to outside temperature.  Drivers and customers will continue to inspect loads as policy states.

column168: Driver and vehicle was headed west on Colorado 24 at mm 446 when the right tire drifted off the roadway, the driver jerked the wheel to get the vehicle back on the roadway, resulting in an oversteer and loss of control.  Vehicle tractor and trailer rolled over releasing product.  Both tractor and trailer ended up off the roadway, product spilled out from top cover and from a hole that happened during the road way. Local emergency authorities were called, we were notified and dispatched an Environmental cleanup company for containment.  Ongoing sampling and cleanup continues.

column168: Intermodal yard personnel found a strong odor around cage container PDIU201201. The container held 7 totes of phosphorous pentasulfide.  Norfolk Southern environmental personnel contacted a response contractor and a representative from the consignee about the issue.  SET Environmental and representatives from Eastman Chemical found product residue left on an outlet and cap for one of the totes that was causing the odor.  The residue was cleaned from the tote and the cage container was released for transport to consignee.
column169: The shipper must perform a more thorough inspection of containers before they are released for transportation.

column168: Driver arrived at plant and showed operator paperwork. Operator directed driver to tank, removed cap on line and told driver to offload at that line. Operator offloading driver smelled a strong odor and shut down his air. About the same time the operator came back and gave the driver a signal to stop. Both breathed the vapor and felt tightness in chest. Both were transported to hospital by paramedics treated and released.  Operator was expecting a load of Alum. When driver arrived and showed him the paperwork, we do not believe it was read and the driver was taken to the Alum tank. Tank is marked Alum tank #1 with a health rating placard. Driver should have been more aware and questioned the operator as to the product. Driver said he did notice the alum placard and was only looking at the line.
column169: Driver given an awareness class by the Terminal Manager and driver trainer. Driver has been doing this type of delivery for years and may have been complacent. He was instructed on awareness and stop and call.

column168: DHL personnel working at the warehouse at the SFO International airport, 944 Northfield Road, San Francisco, CA, 94128, called to report a leaking shipment that had been double-bagged, placed into a tote pan and moved outside the building. PSC Environmental were contacted to make arrangements for emergency spill responders to go to SFO for spill clean-up and investigation. The emergency spill responders relayed the following information: the package was comprised of a fiberboard box containing a single glass bottle with a broken plastic lid. The package contained no absorbent material, but it did have a cardboard insert in the bottom of the box to help stabilize the glass bottle. The shipment contained a total of 4liters, of which approximately 1 pint leaked. The spill response team bagged the shipment, cleaned the spill on the warehouse floor and took the shipment away for disposal. Transport via air was confirmed.

column168: EMI JOB #35267/CON-WAY TRUCKLOAD, INC.- INCIDENT #2014-061354; ON 06-09-14, A CON-WAY TRUCKLOD, INC. (CTI) TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT (TRAILER #44387) ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY TO DELIVER A LOAD OF PRODUCTS. THE PRODUCTS WERE CLASS 3 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND NON-REGULATED MATERIALS. THE MATERIALS WERE PACKAGED IN 55-GALLON DRUMS, 5-GALLON PAILS, AND CARTONS. WHILE UNLOADING THE ITEMS, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 55-GALLON DRUM (UN1210, PRINTING INK, 3,PG II) WAS LEAKING IN THE CTI TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION OF THE DRUM, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS WEEPING FROM THE SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM (PACKAGING FAILURE). LESS THAN ONE PINT OF THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED AND IMPACTED A SMALL AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE DAMAGED DRUM.  NO FURTHER ACTION WAS REQUIRED
column169: Continue our on going efforts in driver safety/spill prevention training in efforts in preventing incidents as these from happening.

On 20/06/2014 at 0400 CST, a bulk CO2 tractor trailer (11975/44045) was traveling W on US HWY 290 (Houston TX, USA).  Traffic came to an abrupt stop due to an ealier accidnet.  The Linde vehicle could not stop in time and struck two separate third party tractor trailers on the road. As a result there was significant damage to the Linde trailer and piping, resulting in the release of CO2 and loss of pressure on the tanker. Approximately 500 Lbs of CO2 was released. All three vehicles involved needed to be towed from the scene. Hazmat crews were dispatched to clean up the released hydraulic oil (from the trailer hydraulic pumping system). No injuries were sustained.
column169: Linde will continue training drivers to be aware and reinforce distration elimination practices for drivers to remain focused on the changing traffic picture.

column168: On June 17th at 1640 personnel in the CSXT Hamlet Yard discovered ACFX87108, a loaded tank car of Cyclohexanone dripping product from bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Honeywell International was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2014-0617-00283.  SWS Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a deteriorated bottom outlet valve cap gasket.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Honeywells representative Dennis Evan at 440-708-8202.  Contractor personnel replaced the gasket and properly secured the car for transportation.  This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 580  bottom outlet cap gasket deteriorated    5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60 NARRI

column168: On June 24th at 1928 hours a train crew was switching rail cars in the CSXT/ NS Cosgrove Yard and discovered GAMX12027, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid leaking from the top of the car.  The conductor switching the tank car was slightly splashed on his ears and neck area with the released material.  The conductor decontaminated the area with water and refused any additional medical treatment.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Honeywell International was contacted via CHEMTREC report number 2014-0624-00277.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to a misaligned fill hole cover gasket.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Honeywells representative Dennis Evan at 440-708-8202.  Contractor personnel properly aligned the gasket, secured the fill hole bolts/nuts with a wrench and decontaminated the container.  The leak was secured and the car was released to destination. This incident did not require a special switching move.    NAR Cause Code: 232  fill hole cover gasket misaligned.    5(5+5+0) x (2+2) = 200 NARRI

A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector inspecting rail cars in the railyard reported that during inspection of tank car NATX 302024 its vacuum relief valve (VRV) was noted venting vapors. Contract responders were called and relieved the internal pressure within NATX 302024 ending the VRV vent. In the morning of 6/20/2014, the same contract responders removed the VRV and a pipe plug was secured into the VRV vacated orifice. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The valve housing cover was resealed with seal TIS 5208. A visual inspection of the removed VRV revealed no obvious cause of failure. No liquid commodity release was associated with this incident.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Lafayette F.D. responded to a call of a strange odor across the street from the BNSF railyard. Investigation of the odor source resulted in finding tank car UTLX 27532 emanating a commodity odor in the railyard. UTLX 27532 was cordoned-off in the railyard and all switching operations ceased. Authorities recommended an evacuation of two business entities adjacent to the railyard, but the evacuation was not fully implemented due to their normal business closure time was imminent. One employee from the Lafayette Utilities System (LUS) complained of inhalation exposure and was taken to a local medical facility for examination and was released afterwards.   Inspection of UTLX 27532 determined the reclosing pressure relief valve (PRV) was venting and was the odor source. Responders placed a capping kit over the PRV to seal off commodity vapors. Afterwards, UTLX 27532 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard further away from the neighboring community. UTLX 27532 continued to be monitored. The probable cause of the PRV vent was commodity overloading of UTLX 27532. Air monitoring was initiated and continued through-out the commodity transfer process with no unacceptable air quality issues found in the railyard and the adjacent/nearby residential and business communities.   On 6/06/2014 contract responders arrived to set-up and begin transfer of the commodity from UTLX 27532 into two other suitable railcars. The commodity transfer began at 1230 hrs. CDT and stopped at 1930 hrs. CDT due to impending darkness per the request from the in charge Louisiana State Police representative. On 6/07/2014 the transfer of the commodity resumed at 0645 hrs. CDT and was completed by 1630 hrs. CDT without further incident. These two receiving tank cars were forwarded to the shipper facility at Lake Charles, LA. On 6/08/2014 all chlorine vapors were removed from UTLX 27532 and scrubbed into totes of 20% caustic solution. After pressure within UTLX 27532 was 0 psi and then a vacuum condition noted, UTLX 27532's PRV was removed and replaced with another suitable PRV.
column169: The shipper has initiated corrective action with procedural changes to ensure rail cars are not overloaded.

column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: EMHU 830205 was observed to have released acid to the outside of the container and onto three other pieces of rail equipment. Upon inspection, twenty-three automotive batteries were found tipped over in the nose of the container. The batteries were palletized and the top two tiers of batteries fell over due to insufficient shrink wrap on the unit. The batteries which fell over spilled a total of five gallons of acid to the floor of the container and to the three other pieces of equipment. All four pieces of equipment were cleaned. The damaged batteries were placed into poly drums.  The material was replaced into the container and the container was then allowed to continue to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: A bulk tank vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. was dispatched to off load at the Safety Kleen Systems Inc. rail site in Portland, OR. Upon completion of the off loading process the driver uncoupled the discharge hose connections and discovered the hose was not completely cleared of waste which caused a release of the discharge hose contents. Upon realization of the release the driver contacted his dispatcher who initiated an in house response. The response crew donned the proper PPE and remediated the impacted area by deploying the appropriate absorbent material. All material collected in the response to this event was containerized and disposed of at a licensed waste management facility. The Oregon Emergency Management Division was notified. OEMD report # 2014-1320.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was determined that the cause of this release was directly related to the driver not following proper off loading procedures. The driver will undergo additional training and counseling relating to proper off loading procedures.  The retraining will focus on the proper coupling and uncoupling of discharge hoses per company policy.

column168: A Univar driver arrived at this customer site at approximately 4:30 pm on 6/18/14.  He was in the process of delivering (1) poly drum of Steol KS-460 when he rolled the drum from the van trailer onto the dock.  As the drum came down on the dock the bottom of the container split open approximately nine inches releasing an estimated 15 gallons of material.  The driver estimated the container dropped approximately 3-5 inches from the rear of the trailer to the loading dock.  The spilled product was immediately cleaned up with absorbent and pig pads and placed into an overpack recovery drum that was returned to the shipping site.  The Univar driver cleaned the spill with no assistance from the customer or an outside agency.
column169: The supplier of the product was informed of the incident.  They completed an investigation that included contacting the drum manufacture (Grief).  They reported no other similar incidents with this product or container type.  This incident was considered an isolated event from the supplier side.  The Univar employees were briefed on the incident and an internal report/investigation was documented.

column168: At 12:16 hrs. EST on 06/16/14, ERTS was contacted by Randy Dieter from CTL Distribution in reference to a leaking drum of UN1261 Nitromethane, a class 3 and the PG is II. Per the driver it appeared that a lid was loose on one of the drums and approximately 8 gallons of material evaporated. There was no impact to either the soil, asphalt, water ways or drains. An ERTS network contractor arrived onsite and over packed and secured the leaking drum and left it on the trailer to continue on to it's destination.

column168: Tank car CGTX 30461 at the railyard's repair track to correct a wheel assembly defect was reported leaking commodity from its top valve housing area.  Contract responders inspecting CGTX 30461 reported the leak source was at the base of the liquid valve that was loose on its threaded connection onto its mounting flange's pipe riser. Also, the liquid valve's applied thread sealant appeared old with signs of degradation. The valve's threaded area was cleaned and new PTFE pipe thread sealant was applied. The liquid valve was then properly tool tightened on its threaded connection. The vapor valve was also removed and its threaded area was cleaned with new pipe thread sealant applied. The vapor valve was re-applied on its threaded connection and tool tightened. CGTX 30461 was pressurized to 15 psi by inserting compressed nitrogen and no further leakage from the liquid valve fitting was observed. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Spillage on the valve housing plate and side shell was wiped and cleaned. There was no ground impact from spillage associated with this incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On June 6, 2014, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container TCNU988033-0 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1950, AEROSOLS class 2.1). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation.

On June 11, 2014, an 80-gallon overpack container containing a 15-gallon drum of UN1791 Hypochlorite Solution was found to be leaking due to the overpack drum being incompatible with the cargo. Approximately one gallon of product was released to a dock floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup activities.

column168: At approximately 05:50 river was en route to a customer making a turn at an intersection and was proceeding too fast. The liquid in the cargo tanker shifted from side to side and the resulting surge caused the tractor and tanker to tip over on its side. Emergency vehicles arrived at the scene at allowed a wrecker service to upright the tractor and cargo tanker. The equipment was towed to a secure yard.The dome of the tanker began slowly leaking while the cargo tanker was on its side. This slow leak last for about 2 hours. A small amount of material leaked onto the highway (approximately 3 gallons) and did not enter any ditches,drains, or waterways. The spilled material was cleaned up and removed by a response contractor.
column169: A stand down meeting was conducted with all drivers the day of the incident to advise of incident and discuss preventative measures such as controlling speed when negotiating turns and curves.All cargo tanker drivers will be trained on Cargo Tanker Rollover Prevention techniques.

A UPS SUPERVISOR OBSERVED SOME BATTERIES COMING OUT OF THE BOX AND ALSO SAW A SPARK. UPON INVESTIGATION, THE BOX WAS WARM TO THE TOUCH AND CHARRED ON THE INSIDE, SO I WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA. CHARRING WAS EVIDENT ON SEVERAL BATTERIES IN THE BOX, SOME OF WHICH APPEARED TO BE LOOSE OR NOT ENCLOSED SECURELY INSIDE PLASTIC BAGS DUE TO THEIR LARGE SIZE. NO CAUSE FOR THE OUTER BOX FAILURE WAS DETERMINED. ALTHOUGH THE CHARRING OF THE FIBERBOARD IS SUSPECTED AS A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR. NO INJURES OR DAMAGE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX OCCURRED.

It was reported that a tractor trailer had a mechanical failure that resulted in a fire that resulted in the release of approximately 38,000 lbs. of material. The material was shipped in 55 gallon poly drums that was compromised by the fire.

THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE RT SIDE. THE DRIVER OVERCORRECTED AND LOST CONTROL. THE TRUCK ROLLED ACROSS THE ROADWAY AND ENDE DUP ON ITS SIDE ON THE OPPOSITE SHOULDER. FUEL WAS LEAKING FROM THE DOME LIDS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT BUILT LIKES TO CONTAINT THE FUEL IN A SMALL AREA. A VACUUM TRUCK AND ANOTHER TANK WAGON WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN UP THE CONTAINED FUEL. THE APPROXIMATE TIME OF THE RELEASE WAS ABOUT 3.5 HOURS.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: A vehicle operated by Safety Kleen Systems was at the Safety Kleen facility in Amityville, NY for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container was discovered with a pin hole leak in the bottom chime of a drum had occured. Internal response personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the leak. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. The New York DEC was notified (report #1403440) and did not respond to site.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver was reinstructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before shipping and acceptance for transportation;if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.The shipper was also notified to conduct inspections prior to loading for shipment.

column168: ERTS was notified of a release coming from a Schneider National trailer #TA941709.  Upon checking the trailer it was discovered that one 15 gallon drum, of Eco-Star Sour VII, a liquid laundry product, containing fluorosilicic acid solution, had a puncture on the bottom of the drum at the outside edge of the plastic drum.  It looks like a sharp protrusion had caused the puncture.  The floor of the trailer was impacted, along with an area of asphalt under the trailer approximately 3'x3' and then going along the trailer impacting an area of asphalt approximately 1'x20'.  The product never impacted any soil, water ways, or drains.  The drums with product on were cleaned along with the trailer floor after the free liquid product had been absorbed.  The asphalt area under the trailer had the free product absorbed up and then wiped down to get any residue product.

The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

It was reported that approximately 20 (twenty) gallons of material was released to a concrete dock area as a result of a tow motor fork puncture. Facility personnel were able to place the tote on it's side to limit any further product release. Facility personnel conducted the subsequent clean up on site by the use of a granular absorbent. An environmental contractor was called out to perform a product transfer from the damaged tote to a replacement tote. No drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted.

column168: (A) On June 27th, 2014 at 06:29 hours, personnel in the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered ACFX 95051, a loaded UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil tank car to have wetness down the side of the tank car, coming from around the manway. The car was isolated and the Shipper, DPTS Marketing, LLC, was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2014-06-27-00065. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, EP+S of Vermont the Buffalo Branch office was dispatched to the scene, upon inspection it was determined that manway cover swing bolts #4+ #5 to be less than tool tight, causing a release of product between the manway cover gasket and the nozzle, the gasket was inspected, replaced due to being crushed and misalgined, the manway nozzle was wipe down and the cover was re-secured and tool tightened. Mr.Paul Ferguson, Rail Logistics Manager, Cell: 612-849-0628 was notified of the situation found and the corrective action taken. ACFX 05051 was released for transport. This incident DID require a special move. column168: On June 20, 2014, a 20-gallon drum containing UN1791 Hypochlorite Solution was punctured by a forklift resulting in the release of an estimated three gallons of material to the dock floor. column168: CN Mechanical department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car TCIX 21109 (Residue Last Contained / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during switching operations at the CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, La. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the vapor valve was left in the open position and a loading attachment was still attached to the vapor valve flange.  The vapor valve was closed and the loading flange was removed.  The vapor valve blind flange was installed and the leak was secured. The railcar was deconned to remove a small amount of product off the top of the tank car. Tank car released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column42: ENGINES INTERNAL COMBUSTION, OR ENGINES, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID POWERED
column168: LOADER DISCOVERED AN ODOR OF GASOLINE COMING FROM THIS BOX. SUPERVISORS AND HAZMAT RESPONDER ISOLATED THE PACKAGE AND UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE CARTON CONTAINED A 3100 WATT GENERATOR THAT WAS FILLED OF 1.8 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. THIS PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP ON A RS-CALL TAG AND WAS BEING RETURNED TO SHIPPER. THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE AT THE ENCLOSURE WHICH QUICKLY EVAPORATED. NO ONE GOT HURT OR REQUIRED ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION FROM THIS BOX.
column169: EDUCATE CUSTOMERS OF PROPER PACKING PROCEDURES FOR LIQUIDS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Driver loaded 20T in Lima,OH. Proceeded S. on I-75 to Versailles,OH. Received call on CB "blowing smoke" out the top of trailer. Looked for a safe spot to pull off. pulled onto the SB exit ramp at Exit 92. Checked wind direction for safety. Called 911.Time 1000 hrs.Called office. DHT routed empty trailer from 20 miles away to off load product.Fire Dept evacuated 1 mile radius and closed I75 for safety. Water was directed at release to dissipate ammonia vapor.Propane service manager enroute to oversee offloading. Remaining product offloaded onto empty trailer. Inspection performed by Off. Dave Staudt,OH Motor Carrier HM Div, Tom Forbes OH PUCO, and Brent Bender, DHT. Top and center of Rear semi internal relief valve gone. 2" hole into the vessel through the relief body.Clean up consisting of washing down the pavement and grass completed. I75 re-opened at 1700 hrs. Trl released from scene 1730 hrs. Trl returned to DHT Reese,MI and cleared for entry. Michigan State HM Investigator William Clarke Jr. and DHT Propane service manager removed the relief shell and forward relief valve. Entered vessel.  Found the lower portion of the through shaft, support collar and the spring from the failed valve. Shaft had been cracked part way through and broken off.This caused a catastrophic valve failure.
column169: Have replaced all Fisher H5112-265 valves in trailers that we own. (2 such valves in fleet)with Marshall 2" semi-internal valve approved for transport. Better design and greater support for the shaft.  Fisher has reported to us when contacted about this valve, that they no longer recommend this valve for transport vehicles, although no recall was in place. A communication from Fisher to transport owners, transport test and repair facilities  would seem to be in order.  As of the date of this follow up report, 01/22/2015, Fisher has issued a voluntary safety recall on these valves used in transport vehicles.  September 2014 vibration testing revealed that in transport applications under certain road conditions these valves can experience excessive bending stresses that could result in fatigue in the valve stem over time.  We are certain that is what occurred in our situation.

column168: A Tote of NA1993 was punctured and released approximately 130 gallons of product out of the trailer and onto a parking area. A vacuum truck was utilized to recover the product from the storm drain.The contractor recovered approximately 150 gallons of impacted water from the storm drain that the trailer drove over. The tote appeared to have been leaking when it arrived. Cause of leak may have been caused by a load shift. column168: A UN2922 release occurred at 0850 EST at a R&L Terminal, 50 Harrison Ave., Kearny, NJ. It was advised that one 55-gallon drum of UN2922 was punctured by a forklift.  Atlantic Response arrived onsite and advised that 1 qt had been released to the concrete floor at the terminal. The leak was  plugged and the drum was over packed.

Packaged was pulled from sort due to odor. No spill but once checked for leak dueto odor 54 l-2oz bottles of undeclared perfume were inside package. Package placed in drum and being held for FAA inspection. Contacted Gary Mohr via phone and left message about spill. I am sending 5800, contact information, and pictures to Gary via email.

HE CONFIRMS THIS IS AUTOMOTIVE PAINT. WE REQUESTED A MSDS BUT THE SHIPPER HAS NO IDEA WHAT THIS IS. SPILL CLEANED LOCALLY AND SHIPMENT SECURED IN SALVAGE DRUM. HELD AT LOCATION FOR FAA INSPECTION. FAA ADVISED VIA PHONE 6-30/BRYAN BUCHANAN. PICTURES REQUESTED FROM AFW.

column168: On 6/17/2014 the truck from Demeter Transport was involved in an auto accident with another semi-truck.  The specific facts of the accident are not known.  The accident caused the Demeter Transport truck to lay over on its side.  This caused the tank on the Demeter Transport truck to rupture leaking approximately 1000 gallons of liquid fertilizer onto the roadway and soil on the side of the highway.    US Environmental Services were called to the scene to perform the clean up of the spill.  They excavated 280 cubic yards of soil from the shoulder of the highway and took it to Eagle Pass Municipal Landfill for disposal.  At the time of clean up the soil was PH'd and verified it was neutral and not acidic.    The roadway was pressure washed prior to the excavation.  The area was backfilled to pre-loss condition per TXDOT standards.
column169: N/A

column168: Company driver/operator left hose/nozzle unattended while dispersing fuel and he went to the vehicle to increase the pressure flow, therefore the nozzle/hose dislodged from fill pipe and fuel then spilled out onto customers pavement until the operator was able to hit the emergency shut-down switch. This incident was caused by human error and failure to follow common delivery procedures.
column169: Extra highlighted training will be conducted pertaining to common and standard industry practice and delivery procedures. The company already provides extensive training in delivery procedures and will continue to improve where necessary.

column168: Dockworker damaged two cartons and a total of two cans with forklift during loading process.  Reported release to supervisor.  Supervisor called safety department for release handling determination.  After review of the SDS, safety determined material was unsafe for terminal to clean up based on the type of PPE required and low flashpoint.  Emergency response vendor contacted to handle clean up.  Trailer moved to safe distance from terminal with door open to vent until arrival of clean up crew.

column168: THE KAG WEST, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD THE TRAILER WAS DIESEL FUEL. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE OVERFILLED THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY 380 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED. A MAJORITY OF THE SPILLED DIESEL FUEL WAS ISOLATED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE OVERFILL PROTECTION GAUGE ON THE TRAILER FAILED TO SHUT DOWN THE FLOW OF DIESEL FUEL INTO THE TRAILER. BIG SKY ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KAG WEST, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE UNLOADING/LOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

Customer had a leaking 55 gallon poly drum of a concentrated corrosive that was overpacked in a 85 metal container.  The customer requested Clean Harbors to pump out the leaking drum into another DOT approved container.  During the pump out process there was a failure with the stinger rod causing the pump to surge which released approximately 5 gallons of material onto the floor.  Clean Harbors immediately shut down the pump.  The immediate area was cleanup.  All material used to clean up the area was containerized and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Reminded the Customer that in the future, any drum failures that occur at their facility should be placed in the appropriate type Salvage Drums.

column168: On June 26, 2014, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container TCNU956512-7 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN1950 Aerosols Class 2.1). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

Per supervisor report, Driver arrived at the wright 6 lease, worked the oil in the two tanks he had dispatched to him. Tank 2 had 144 and tank 3 had 100 (173BBLS). He went to the back valves and opened the valve on tank 3  and intended to open tank 2  to equalize the tanks so he would have two full loads rather than one full and one short load, he heard something and went to the front of the tanks and discovered oil running out of the EPA box for the water draw. The valve on the water draw EPA box had been left open by a water truck driver. He shut the valve and reported the spill. The spilt oil was recovered by a vacuum truck and a load of rock was brought in to cover the spilt area and back drug by a backhoe.
The package of limited quanties, overpack, was crushed by ULD system. Small amount of actual leakage. Class 9 material ( Locktile )
column169: The contrator will excerise great care when using the UD loading system and place cargo in the path of the ULD weighing/loading system. Damages by this system are very rare.

column168: Clean Harbors employee was placing a customer's 55 gallon poly drum in the back of a box truck and as he turn away to exit, he notice a small amount leaking from the bottom of the drum.  The drum was quickly laid on its side to stop the leak.  The spilled material was cleaned up and the clean-up debris along with the damaged drum were placed into a Salvage Drum.  The container was sent for disposal to the intended disposal facility.
column169: In order to prevent recurrence, the Clean Harbors employee was reminded to carefully inspect all containers before placing them in a Clean harbors vehicle.

column168: US Xpress notified ERTS at 10:45 EST of a release of an approximately 5 gallons of UN1993, Flammable Liquid n.o.s, at 1641 Musgrave Blvd, Abilene, TX. The release impacted the trailer floor.The Contractor reported that they off loaded the drums to reach the drum that caused the release. It was reported that one drum released approximately 5 gallons of material to the trailer floor. It was reported that there were two small pin holes in the 55 gallon drum. The contractor epoxied the holes and  reloaded the trailer.

At 0455 ET hours, Tina Breezley of R&L Carriers contacted ERTS regarding a release of approximately 3/4 of a gallon of a UN1791 HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION to the floor of a trailer from a leaking 330 gallon tote. At the time of this report, no drains, soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. ERTS has requested copies of the BOL and MSDS in order to determine if RQ has been met or exceeded. RQ for Sodium Hypochlorite is 100 pounds. ERTS will make any required regulatory reporting. ERTS has dispatched a network contractor with an approximate 2 hour ETA to site. The shipper is Nexeo Solutions. ERTS was advised by Tina Breezley that she will notify Chemtrec.Facility personnel were able to turn tote on it's side to prevent further release of product and an environmental contractor performed the product tote transfer.

On 06/21/2014, HOKX 8019 was reported to leaking product from the bottom. UP hazmat was notified and NRC environmental was also dispatched to perform all necessary decontamination. Upon arrival a full inspection was performed on the tank car. It was verified that the car leaked. The top operated bottom outlet valve was 1 full turn into the open position. Allowing product to seep through main valve and leak through cap. The valve was secured and decon complete.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Manway or Dome Cover
column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: Tank car SRIX 23673 entrained on the MHOFW-22 derailed and rolled onto its right side causing approximately 3000 gallons of product to leak from the manway opening into a low depression adjacent the car.  Cause of the release was due to an improperly secured manway cover.  Inspection by response personnel revealed the manway nozzle gasket to be in poor condition and mis-positioned on the manway nozzle.  1 swingbolt in the 4 o'clock position was not in place, and when properly positioned and tightened, the swingbolt at the 6 o'clock position fell from place.  Upon proper placement, and tightening of remaining 7 less than wrench tight swingbolts, the release was minimized to a minor drip and contained within a portable tub.  Further inspection of the car revealed that the manway cover was not impacted or struck resulting from the car rolling onto its right side.  Upon rerailing of the car, there was no further release of product.  On 7-10-14, remaining product in the damaged car was transferred into tank car GAMX 5520 for further handling by the shipper.  Responding environmental contractors recovered released product with the use of a vacuum truck, and excavation of product saturated soil.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: Driver was unloading product to the customer.  Driver heard a "pop" and the unit began venting. Stabilized the unit and returned to terminal for repairs.
column169: Establish a preventative maintenance program for all trailers that includes testing and/or replacement of the safety relief valves and other pressure relief components.

column168: While unloading a semi-van trailer at the Veolia facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI, a leaking drum was observed. Driver was driving north on a two lane highway in the vicinity of Carlsbad, NM on his way to deliver a load of crude oil. This was a normal route that he ran everyday to his unload destination. At one point on County Road 605, the road makes a sharp left turn and the speed limit drops from 65 mph. to 55 mph. As driver, started to slow to go into the turn a deer was standing in the road. Driver panicked and locked up his brakes and went off the road resulting in the tractor trailer rolling over.
column169: A safety blitz was conducted company wide to increase awareness about preventing rollovers and what to do if ananimal is in the road. Safety Meetings will be held to discuss rollover prevention, as well as, ongoing training to minimize the possibility of future rollovers and spills.

column168: Facts indicated are collected from Vessel reporting and Surveyor Report:    June 9, 2014: Subject cargo loaded the Akinada Bridge V 74A at Shanghai, China with a final port of discharge, Savannah, GA, however, was off-loaded at Port Newark per COTP directive.  June 30, 2014: While vessel was enroute to the USA, the Master reported leakage from container KKTU 7468640 onto the hatch over.  July 9, 2014: Container KKTU774358 (belonging to the same cargo interests) and stowed on top of the first container was also noted leaking which spilled on top and side of the lower container.  Measures taken by the Vessel included:  • Use of drip trays were used to collect the continuous slow drip of liquid.  Approximately 1.5 liters was collected in the drip trays, however, a more substantial amount leaked on the deck and was noted on the hatch cover that the containers were stowed on and on the deck nearby.    •The Vessel ensured there was no heat source, cordoned off the area and crew members were not let close due to the inhalation hazard.    •Incident details were recorded by the Vessel as SOP    USCG issued a Safety Order which was later rescinded.  USCG required the leaking containers be discharged as 1st US Port of Call at Maher Terminals in Newark, NJ after reviewing and approving a Response Plan drawn up by Gallagher Marine (QI).    All actions (July 9-11) upon discharge were approved by the USCG who mostly were in attendance.  Cargo was transloaded into other ocean containers upon clean up.     The Surveyor noted the solid crystals at ambient temps, is hydroscopic and apparently absorbed moisture from the air in transit from high humidity and temperature variations causing some of it to liquefy, as it is soluble.  The liquid flowed out of the NON-WATER TIGHT bags IBCs (13H4).  When the  liquid evaporated later over a period of days, the remaining residue in white powder form was left on the deck and hatch covers.      1.5 Liters (collected in drip trays, HOWEVER, a larger quantity was released onto the Vessel.  Vessel did not provide estimated amount though.
column169: The surveyor advised that it appears the Insufficient Packing was a direct cause of the leak, which could have been prevented if the product had been shipped in plastic drums, for example.

column168: An overpacked drum labeled Molanic Acid was picked up from Shipper/Offerer.    A vehicle operated by Safety-Kleen Systems, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transfer operation, the over-pack drum was discovered to be reacting causing an escape of  approximately 5 gallons.  The contingency spill plan was effected.  All proper notification was made.  The local Fire Department was notified and was on site so as to ensure no further reaction.  In-house response team suited up using proper personal protection equipment, removed the drum from the truck, and placed it in a containment area.  With the material stabelized and identified as Hydrochloric Acid, it was then overpacked into a suitable over-pack drum.  All areas of the truck, drums and surrounding area were neutralized and decontaminated.    In addition, all clean-up debris were collected and placed into am appropriate salvage drum. Once completed, the container was marked, labeled, secured and then placed onto a trailer for continued transportation.
column169: A Management Team Investigation was conducted.  We retested the drum and found it did not contain Malonic Acid (as designated by the generator, Allied Building), rather Hydrochloric Acid.  The profile was immediately expired and we contacted the generator.  We went back to the generator to educate and discuss the fact that SKS was acting on generator knowledge and that all must be certain of what is being packaged and prepared for transport. And if the generator is uncertain then we need to have appropriate samples pulled to determine up front what will be disposed of.  We also conducted training and counseling sessions with the Field Representative, the Market Sales Specialist and the Customer Service Manager on how a drum of this nature should be handled and addressed before picking it up in the future. Part of the retraining was proper drum handling procedures as well as overpacking a drum.  This training was also conducted to the whole branch to make sure it was stressed with all associates who handle these types of situations.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: June 26, 2014: CR Risk Management A. Richter contacted by CR Mechanical Superintendent R. Rose, advising tank car GATX 33350, load, Toxic Liquids, Organic, NOS (Dimethyl Maleate, Class 6.1, III) was actively leaking from the pressure relief device, while on track #1 Middle at CR's Oak Island Yard, Newark, NJ.  Car was moved by Transportation Department to track 64 for ease of access to car by response personnel. Further inspection by CR's Richter, and representatives from Hepaco, a Conrail emergency response contractor, noted the car was a dual compartmented tank car.  "A" end compartment containing Acetone; and the "B" end compartment containing Toxic Liquids, Organic, NOS.  Product cascading down from the "B" end pressure relief valve.  Attempt to depressure the car via the "B" end air valve was unsuccessful due to liquid coming out of said valve.  As the ambient temperature began to drop, the car stopped releasing product but had begun agin intermittently until eventually stopping on its own. Representatives of the shipper, IMTT Terminals, Bayonne, NJ (and their emergency response contractor, EQ) supplied a vacuum truck and pulled off approximatly 250 gallons of product.  "B" end manway cover was opened and product level was down to approximately 11" from the bottom of the manway nozzle.  Car secured and okayed for forwarding on for transportation. A pile of old wheat-type substance was under the car where the product was dripping from car, and absorbed the product.  The saturated wheat was cleaned up and disposed of as required, by Hepaco.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: A TANKER TRAILER (TT-221) CONTAINING SPM (SULFURIC PEROXIDE MIXTURE) WAS STAGED AT OUR YARD FOR A PERIOD OF STORAGE INCIDENTAL TO TRANSPORTATION. A GEC EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE BALL VALVE GASKET AT 1900 ON 06-22-14. THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR ON CALL AND BEGAN TAKING STEPS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL USING ABSORBENT PADS. ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEES RESPONDED AT ONCE, EACH OF WHICH HAS BEEN TRAINED TO, AT LEAST, THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN LEVEL AS DEFINED AT 29 CFR 1910.120(Q)(6)(III).WORKERS ISOLATED THE EQUIPMENT. IN ADDITION, TEAM MEMBERS CREATED A DIRT BERM AND CATCH POND TO PREVENT THE PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE PUBLIC RIGHT OF WAY. INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING UNIT RESULTED IN THE DETERMINATION THAT THE GASKET BETWEEN THE TANK AND THE REAR AIR-ACTUATED VALVE FAILED, CAUSING THE SPM TO LEAK OUT AND TO EXPOSE EQUIPMENT PARTS IN CLOSE PROXIMITY TO THE ACID. THE LEAK WAS INITIALLY SLOWED BY TIGHTENING THE AFFECTED BOLTS CONNECTING THE REAR VALVE TO THE TANK. EQUIPMENT TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TANKER WAS LOCATED AND MOBILIZED TO THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 01:30 ON 06-23-14, THE NECESSARY EQUIPMENT ARRIVED ON SITE AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TT-219. THE TRANSFERRED MATERIAL WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S DESIGNATED LOCATION ON 06-23-14. REMEDIATION BEGAN IMMEDIATELY UPON ACHIEVING CONTAINMENT. THE LIQUID IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED USING AN ACTIVATED CAUSTIC SODA MIXTURE THEN PUMPED INTO TOTES (275-GALLON PORTABLE TANKS). SOIL IN THE AREA WAS ALSO NEUTRALIZED USING A POWDER FORM OF THE PREVIOUSLY MENTIONED CAUSTIC SODA MIXTURE. AFFECTED SOIL WAS THEN REMOVED AND PLACED IN TEN (10) 25 YARD ROLL OFF BOXES. EQUIPMENT AND SURFACES WERE DECONTAMINATED WITH WATER THAT WAS ALSO CONTAINERIZED FOR TESTING TO ENSURE NON-HAZARDOUS PROPERTIES. PPE WAS PACKAGED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.   SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM THE CATCH POND AND DOWN GRADE AREA: ONE WAS TAKEN FROM EACH OF THE FOUR SIDES, ONE FROM THE BOTTOM, AND MORE EVERY 20-30 FEET FROM THE CATCH POND AREA IN THE DIRECTION OF POTENTIAL RUN-OFF FOR 150 FEET. ALL SAMPLES WERE EVALUATED AND DETERMINE TO BE UNCONTAMINATED BASED ON PH RESULTS OF A NEUTRAL NATURE. CONFIRMATION SAMPLES WERE SENT TO A CERTIFIED LABORATORY FOR EVALUATION.  THE HOLE WAS LINED WITH POLY TARP AND BACKFILLED WITH 1’ LIFTS. ONCE CONFIRMATION SAMPLES WERE RETURNED AS ACCEPTABLE, BASE MATERIAL WAS ADDED TO MATCH EXISTING GRADE. ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL AND MATERIALS IS CURRENTLY BEING CHARACTERIZED AND PROFILED FOR DISPOSAL INTO A PROPERLY PERMITTED TSDF.  THIS EVENT DID NOT CAUSE A FATALITY OR PERSONAL INJURY, DID NOT CAUSE OR CONTRIBUTE TO AN EVACUATION, DID NOT AFFECT ANY TRANSPORTATION ARTERY, OR CAUSE PROPERTY DAMAGE IN EXCESS OF 50,000. IT WAS CONTAINED SOLELY WITHIN THE SITE BOUNDARIES, DID NOT REACH ANY WATERWAYS, AND WAS CLEANED UP PRIOR TO ANY PRECIPITATION THAT MAY HAVE CREATED CONTAMINATED RUN OFF.
column169: CAUSE  THE GASKET WHICH FAILED DID NOT MEET COMPANY SPECIFICATIONS. IN FEBRUARY 2013, COMPANY CONTRACTED WITH TWO VENDORS TO INSTALL TEFLON GASKETS AT EVERY FLANGE POINT PRIOR TO PLACING TANKER INTO SERVICE.   CORRECTIVE AND PREVENTIVE ACTIONS  INSPECT ALL ACID TANKERS TO ENSURE TEFLON GASKETS ARE INSTALLED ON ALL FLANGE POINTS. REVIEW PROCUREMENT PROCESS, AND REVISE AS NECESSARY, TO ENSURE WRITTEN SPECIFICATIONS OR WORK ORDERS ARE PROVIDED TO VENDORS AND REQUIRED PRODUCTS/SERVICES ARE DELIVERED. REVIEW TANKER INSPECTION PROCEDURE, AND REVISE AS NECESSARY, TO ENSURE DAILY AND PERIODIC INSPECTIONS INCLUDE ALL NECESSARY COMPONENTS, ARE PERFORMED IN AN EFFECTIVE MANNER, AND ANOMALIES COMMUNICATED TO APPROPRIATE PARTIES. TRAIN ALL AFFECTED PARTIES ON CHANGED PROCEDURES AND REINFORCED TRAINING ON UNCHANGED PROCEDURES. EVALUATE TANKER PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE PROCEDURE AND SCHEDULE TO ENSURE IT IS APPROPRIATE TO PACKAGING AND LADING. EVALUATE SPILL RESPONSE FOR ADHERENCE TO PROCEDURES, PLAN ADEQUACY OR REVISION NEEDS, QUALITY OF COMMUNICATION, AND OUTCOME ACHIEVED.

column168: CN IMX Mechanical employees noticed a liquid coming  from the doors of container ZIMU 299156 (L / CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S / UN 3265) during an inspection at CN IMX Terminal, Memphis, Tn.  All appropriate departments notified, container was isolated.  CN response team responded and observed the container was secured with seal # ZIM ZZCN 33914. The container was filled with 13 totes / IBC, 10 on the base layer and 3 stacked on top of the base layer.  The top 3 totes were crushing several of the base totes. The totes were offloaded and 2 leaking totes were discovered.  The leak was determined to be because the lower totes were crushed causing product to leak from the top lid.  The totes were transferred into another container / ZCSU 272033 and all stacked on the base layer.  The 2 damaged totes that were leaking were transferred into other totes. column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING NORTH BOUND ON THE DALTN HIGHWAY. THE RESULT WAS A ROLLED TRACTOR & TRAILER THAT LANDED UPRIGHT. THERE HAD BEEN A NUMBER OF HEAVY RAIN DAYS THAT MIGHT HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE SOFT SHOULDER (THE ROAD IS NOT PAVED). ONCE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED THE PROPER AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED & INITIAL RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED. WITHIN 24 HRS THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED, SPILL RESPONDERS DISPATCHED & STATE AGENCY SITE INSPECTION. WITHIN 48HRS THE UNIFIED COMMAND CNETER WAS ESTABLISHED, RESPONDERS ON SITE & AGENCY OVERSIGHT. SPILL RESPONSE & CLEAN UP ACTIVITIES OCCURRED OVER A TWO WEEK PERIOD. THE SITE IS CURRENTLY BEING MONITORED.
column169: - ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN TO OUR DRIVERS HIGHLIGHTING THE EFFEECTS OF DISTRACTED DRIVERS.    - WE WILL ALSO PUT TRAINING TOGETHER REINFORCING THE REGIONAL SPECIFIC HAZARDS THAT ARE PRESENT ON THE DALTON HIGHWAY.
