column168: AT THE POINT OF ATTEMPTING TO MAKE AN LP GAS DELIVERY TO 1 HERON LANE HOPEDALE, MA OUT DELIVERY DRIVER, TOM MCGEE, DISCOVERED A PROPANE LEAK AT THE POINT OF THE FILTER STRAINER LOCATED ON THE BOBTAIL TANK. UPON NOTICING LEAK, TOM IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF TRUCK ENGINE, CONTACTED HOPEDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND NOTIFIED OUR OFFICE OF SITUATION. OUR MECHANICS, DELIVERY MANAGER AND SERVICE MANAGER ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY TO HELP SHUT DOWN SOURCE OF LEAK AND ASSIST FIRE DEPT. PERSONNEL. SEE NARRATIVE FROM HOPEDALE FORE DEPARTMENT FOR DETAILS.
column169: AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WE INSTALLED A HIGH PRESSURE 1/4 TURN VALVE THAT WILL ISOLATE ANY FUTURE LEAKS AND PREVENT THE LEAK FOR EMITTING INTO ATMOSPHERE AND THERFORE WILL NOT BE A FURTHER THREAT TO SOCIETY. IT WOULD BE IDEAL IF THE MANUFACTURER OF ALL PROPANE BOBTAIL TANKS WERE REQUIRED TO INSTALL THIS ADDITIONAL APPARATUS PRIOR TO SALE OF EQUIPMENT.

column168: DRUMS RUBBING TOGETHER DURING TRANSPORTATION CAUSED A SMALL HOLE IN THE LOWER PART OF ONE DRUM. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WOKE OUR DRIVER WHILE THE SLEEPER OF THE POSSIBLE LEAK. THEY NOTICED A PUDDLE ON THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER. AT WHICH TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PUMPED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL HAD THEIR CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR ARRIVE ON SITE TO CLEAN THE CONCRETE WHERE THE TRAILER WAS PARKED. THEY PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN OVERPACK. THIS PROCESS TOOK APPROXIMATELY 5 HOURS TO COMPLETE.
column169: Our drivers have been instructed to look for drums that could possibly rub together during transport and have the shipper separate them accordingly.

column168: THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM THE TRAILER WHILE HE WAS STOPPED AT A TRUCKSTOP. THE DRIVER CALLED US ECOLOGY AND REPORTED THE LEAK. US ECOLOGY CALLED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT, INC. AND A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL CREW DONNED LEVEL B, PPE IN ORDER TO ENTER TRAILER. UPON ENTRY, THE CREW OBSERVED THAT SEVERAL DRUMS WERE BULGING. ONE DRUM NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING. A FORKLIFT WAS REQUIRED TO REMOVE SOME OF THE FREIGHT FOR THE CREW TO ACCESS THE LEAKING DRUM. THE FORKLIFT ARRIVED ON SITE AND PART OF THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED TO ALLOW ACCESS. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS METAL AND HAD CORRODED THE BUNG HOLE THREADS TO THE POINT THAT THE LIQUID SLOSHED OUT OF THE DRUM DURING TRANSPORT. THE LIQUID WAS FOUND SPLASHED ONTO ANOTHER DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 5 TO 10 SQ. FT. OF FLOOR AREA HAD BEEN IMPACTED. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED (INVERTED) INTO A 95-GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM, LABELED AND LEFT NEAR THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE CREW SLOWLY LOOSENED THE BUNGS ON APPROXIMATELY 30 DRUMS TO RELIEVE PRESSURE AND REDUCE BULGING. THE CREW WIPED ALL CONTAMINATION FROM THE DRUMS, PALLETS AND EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER. THE CREW USED SODA ASH AND CLAY ABSORBENTS TO DECONTAMINATE THE FLOOR AND THE CONCRETE UNDER THE TRAILER. THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS AND THE CREW PPE WERE PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON POLY DRUM, LABELED AND ADDED TO THE MANIFEST. THE TRAILER WAS THEN READY FOR TRANSPORT.
column169: NO DESCRIPTION INCLUDED.

column168: 06/13/14 TIME:2203:  OUR DRIVER ARRIVED ON SITE TO DELIVER LOAD AT 2203 HOURS.  HE BEGAN HIS DELIVERY AND MISTAKENLY DELIVERED REGULAR PRODUCT INTO THE B5 TANK.  THE APPROPRIATE STAFF WAS NOTIFIED AND THE DIESEL PUMPS WERE SHUT OFF TO PREVENT ANY SALES OF THE BAD PRODUCT.  OUR HARRIS DRIVER ARRIVED WITH THE PUMP TRUCK AND BEGAN SETTING UP THE PUMP OUT PROCESS. HE THEN BEGAN TO PUMP OUT THE TANK INTO OUR TRUCK. THE PUMP OUT WAS GOING WELL; TRUCK 380/381 WAS COMPLETELY LOADED WITH 9452 GALLONS OF GAS/DIESEL MIX.  THE DRIVER THEN BEGAN TO LOAD TRUCK #408/409. DURING THE TIME WE WERE PUMPING INTO #380, THE PRESSURE HOSE BURST AND SPRAYED THE MIX. A DRIVER WAS STANDING BY THE PUMP AND IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THE THREE HARRIS DRIVERS THAT WERE ON SITE BLOCKED IN ALL THE VALVES, GRABBED THEIR SPILL KITS, AND BEGAN TO CLEAN UP THE RELEASE. THE ATTENDANT ON SITE VOLUNTEERED MORE DIAPERS THAT OUR DRIVERS ACCEPTED.  WE DISPATCHED SOME ADDITIONAL STAFF TO THE SITE TO ASSIST IN THE LAST PART OF THE CLEANUP.  ON JUNE 17TH HARRIS TRANSPORTATION ARRANGED FOR RANDY BOESE, BB&A ENVIRONMENTAL, REVIEW THE INCIDENT, MEET WITH THE SITE OWNER TO CONFIRM THAT THE SITE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND NO CONTAMINATES REMAINED.
column169: THE OREGON FIELD SAFETY SUPERVISOR DRAFTED A PROCEDURE TO ALL HARRIS DRIVERS OUTLINING THE INSPECTION OF PUMP HOSE AND EQUIPMENT PRIOR TO LEAVING THE YARD FOR THE SITE. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED NOTICE FOR FUTURE PREVENTION OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING A PUMP OFF.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: Driver exited truck-stop to parking lot after dining, noticed a leaking drip from external valve, notified company Safety Dept. Safety Dept. contacted U.S.E.S. to respond and transfer cargo of "Nitric Acid-Other Than Red Fuming-Containing at least 65 but less than 70% Nitric Acid" to other Company Owned Tank Trailer. Prior to establishing containment, several gallons of Nitric Acid impacted the asphalt pavement and concrete curbing. U.S.E.S. arrived, established secondary containment and began applying a neutralizing agent to acid pooled against curbing. Several hours later, another Company trailer arrived and U.S.E.S. used diaphram pump to effect transfer from trailer with leaking valve to relief trailer. Relief trailer continued to Consignee. Trailer with leaking gasket was cleaned of exterior acid residue and proceeded to Company maintenance shop for inspection and Root Cause investigation.
column169: Recommendations are to perform inspections on valve gaskets and pneumatic pressure test on each trailer prior to pick-up of Nitric Acid. Correct materials of construction were used. Trailer had been inspected within previous 4 months. Gasket (teflon) failed prematurely. Suspect improper assembly of external valve by tank wash.

column169: This accident happened on a 2 lane county road, where vehicle D2 caused Vehicle D1 to move to the right shoulder ditch resulting in a roll over. It is also recommended more caution must be utilized in observing oncoming vehicles.

column168: ON JUNE 30, 2014, A GASOLINE RELEASE OCCURED FOLLOWING THE RUPTURE OF A COMPARTMENT ON A POPE TRANSPORT TANKER. THE COMPARTMENT WAS RUPTURED WHEN THE TANKER CAME INTO CONTACT WITH A COMMERCIAL SIGN WHILE ATTEMPTING TO TURN AROUND AT A CIRCLE K CONVENIENCE STORE. THE FUEL WAS RELEASED TO AN ASPHALT/CONCRETE SURFACE, FLOWED TO A STORMWATER CATCH BASIN, AND DISCHARGED INTO A WOODED AREA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR RESPONDED. THE DRAIN WAS FLUSHED AND APPROXIMATELY 650 GALLONS OF RINSE WATER WAS RECOVERED. FOUR DRUMS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE ALSO GENERATED. APPROXIMATELY 1,000-TONS OF SOIL WERE EXCAVATED FROM THE WOODED AREA AND TRANSPORTED TO A LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY. CONFIRMATION SAMPLES COLLECTED FROM THE BASE OF THE EXCAVATION WERE BELOW LABORATORY DETECTION LIMITS. THE AFFECTED AREA WAS BACK-FILLED AND LANDSCAPED WITH SEED AND STRAW.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS SOUTHBOUND AND HIT A MOTORHOME TOWING A JEEP IN THE REAR END. AT IMPACT THE E TRACK WAS RIPPED FROM THE INSIDE OF THE VAN BODY WHERE CYLINDERS AND AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK WERE SECURED. UPON IMPACT THE PALLET JACK WAS SLAMMED INTO THE IBC AND PUNCTURED IT APPROXIMATELY 12-14" FROM THE BOTTOM WHICH CAUSED A LEAK. THE PUNCTURE WAS A SPLIT. ATTACHED IS THE REPOSNSE REPORT FROM SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICE, THE COMPANY WE CONTACTED TO ACCESS AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL.

column168: THE FTI TANKER WAS HEADING NORTHBOUND ON STATE ROUTE 65 APPROX 5 MILES NORTH OF LEPSIC, OHIO. THE DRIVER WENT OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND COULD NOT CORRECT RESULTING IN THE VEHICLE ROLLING OVER ON TO ITS SIDE, THE TANK COME TO REST IN APPROX THE POSITION ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. THE ROLLOVER RESULTED IN A CRACK AND SMALL PUNCTURE IN BETWEEN THE 1100 AND 1600 GALLON COMPARTMENTS. THE DAMAGE WAS IN AN AREA THAT COULD NOT BE PATCHED RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF PRODUCTS IN BOTH COMPARTMENTS. A VACCUM TRUCK WAS PLACED AT THIS LOCATION RECOVERING FROM A TRENCH 1300 GALLONS OF THE 2600 RELEASED. THE LEIPSIC FIRE DEPT PLACED JACKS ALONG THE TANKER TO KEEP IT FROM ROLLING OVER AND APPLIED FOAM TO THE AREA. NO PRODUCT MADE IT INTO OPEN WATERWAYS BUT DID ENTER DAY TILE STORM SEWERS THAT WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED. EACH COMPARTMENT WAS DRILLED USING AN DRILL THE 1100 AND 1600 WERE EMPTY. THE PUNCTURE WAS ABOUT THE SIZE OF A PENNY WITH CRACKS GOING HORIZONTAL FROM EACH SIDE. APPROX 500 TONS OF SOIL WAS EXCAVATED FROM THE RELEASE SITE AND 10,500 GALLONS OF WATER AND ETHANOL (1300 GALLONS FROM A TRENCH).

column169: IN AN EFFORT TO HELP AVOID ROLLOVER OUR COMPANY HAS BEEN AGGRESSIVELY REPLACING ALL TRACTOR POWER UNITS THAT DO NOT HAVE A ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEM. BEING A SMALL FLEET WE HAVE SUCCESSFULLY ATTAINED A 74% SATURATION OF TRACTOR POWER UNITS THAT ARE EQUIPPED WITH A ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEM. UNFORTUNATELY THE TRACTOR POWER UNIT IN THIS ACCIDENT IS ONE THAT WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH SUCH A SYSTEM. ADDITIONALLY, THE TRAILER WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH A ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEM. THE TRAILER THAT IS ON ORDER TO REPLACE THE IN THIS ACCIDENT WILL BE EQUIPPED WITH A ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEM, A LOW CENTER OF GRAVITY DESIGN, AIR DISC BRAKES, AND THE WIDEST AXLE TRACK AVAILABLE ALL IN AN EFFORT TO HELP AVOID SUCJ INCIDENTS GOING FORWARD.  WE HAVE ALSO REDUCED FLEET SPEEDS TO 62 MPH AS AN ADDED SAFETY PRECAUTION. ADDITIONAL TRAINING IS BEING PROVIDED TO ALL DRIVERS REGARDING ROLLOVER PREVENTION. ADDITIONALLY WE ARE CLOSELY MONITORING THE UNITS EQUIPPED WITH ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEMS THROUGH OUR PEOPLENET SYSTEM AND PROVIDING FURTHER TRAINING AND GUIDANCE FOR ANY DRIVER TRIGGERING STABILITY AN INTERVENTION BY THE ROLLOVER SYSTEM. A TRIGGER BY THE SYSTEM DOES NOT SIGNAL THAT A ROLLOVER IS EMINENT BUT THAT CONDITIONS ARE APPROACHING THE SAFE THRESHOLD FOR MITIGATION.  RECOMMENDATION- 1. MANDATE THAT ALL TRACTOR POWER UNITS AND CARGO TANKS TRANPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TO BOTH BE EQUIPPED WITH ROLLOVER STABILITY SYSTEMS.  2. EXPLORE NEW DESIGNS IN TANK TRAILERS THAT WILL GREATLY REDUCE COG (CENTER OF GRAVITY).  3.DESIGN & DEVELOP REALISTIC AND AFFORDABLE DRIVING SIMULATORS TO ALLOW DRIVERS TO PRACTICE THEIR DRIVING SKILLS. PERHAPS AS PART OF OBTAINING A CDL MANDATING PASSING A DRIVING SIMULATOR TEST ALONG WITH WRITTEN AND FORMAL DRIVING TEST TO DETERMINE HOW A DRIVER WILL REACT TO ADVERSE CONDITIONS IN A SAFE CONTROLLED ENVIRONMENT.

column168: Driver had finished unloading and disconnected hose from trailer connection placing hose in hose rack, failing to put plug in hose end and closing valve, he then checked pump unit and found it was not running. During this time an additional truck drove up on location to unload and driver walked over to talk with other driver about pump not running. As they walked back toward the pump, driver turned off electric pump switch causing oil to be released from the hose since the valve was open and plug on hose end was not in hose. Approx 1/2 BBL spilled to the containment area within tank farm.  No material exited the containment.
column169: Educate drivers not to turn off pump units until sure all valves are closed and hoses are blocked.

column168: The driver was almost entirely unloaded, standing next to the unload box with his hand resting on the unload hose when the connection gasket gave way.  The display had already zeroed out. There was approx 1 barrel of crude oil left on the trailer when the oil began to spray from the connection. Driver was in position to immediately shut down the pump.  Small amount of oil was collect and gravel removed for disposal by site.
column169: Fully inspect all gaskets prior to installing to ensure that there are no potential points of failure in the gasket.  Shipper is listing this as an equipment failure.

column168: Driver started loading, took samples, specs of the oil were too hight and the driver started to pump crude oil back into tank.  Tank was already full due to incoming product.  It burped oil out of the top of the tank.  Approximately 10 gallons crude oil spilled.
column169: Retrain driver on process of returning product to a tank.  Pump was running at full speed.  Process was modified to reduce pump down to normal speed.

column168: SEVEN DRUMS OF THE 334 DRUMS RECEIVED ON LINE 1 OF NON-HAZARDOUS MANIFEST 51297 WERE SAMPLED AND TESTED ON JULY 30TH AND FOUND TO HAVE A PH OF EQUAL TO OR GREATER THAN 12.5. THE MATERIAL IS DECON WATER, WHICH INCLUDES INDUSTRIAL PURPLE CLEANER AND DEGREASER THAT CONTAINS SODIUM HYDROXIDE. AN UNMANIFESTED WASTE REPORT WAS SUBMITTED TO NYSDEC; THESE DRUMS SHOULD HAVE BEEN CLASSIFIED AS A D002 CORROSIVE HAZARDOUS WASTE. CWM ALSO DETERMINED THAT THESE DRUMS SHOULD HAVE BEEN SHIPPED AS A DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND HENCE IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT.
column169: CWM HAS REQUESTED A PROFILE MODIFICATION TO ADD THE D002 WASTE CODE AND THE DOT SHIPPING NAME OF WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, INORGANIC, NOS. CWM REQUESTED THAT FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF MATERIAL WITH A PH = OR > 12.5 BE ON A HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WITH A DOT SHIPPING NAME OF WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID BASIC, INORGANIC, NOS.

column168: DRIVER HAD PICKED UP A PREVIOUSLY LOADED VAN TRAILER OF DRUM WASTE AT PSC ENVIRONMENTAL, HATFIELD, PA. BEFORE DEPARTING THE FACILITY DRIVER INSPECTED THE LOAD AND FOUND NOTHING WRONG, IT WAS WHILE IN ROUTE TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY THAT A PA STATE POLICE OFFICER PULLED THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE OVER NEAR MILE MARKER 299 ON INTERSTATE 80 BECAUSE THE OFFICER OBSERVED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  STATE POLICE CONTACT NUMEROUS AGENCIES (PADEP, EPA, FIRE, EMS, SPILL RESPONSE ORGANIZATION) AND HAD I-80 SHUT DOWN.    AFTER REVIEWING MANIFEST (APPROX. 6 HOURS LATER), RESPONSE / CLEAN UP CREW WAS ALLOWED TO ENTER THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  A DRUM LOCATED 6 ROWS IN FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE PIN HOLES IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  AFTER DRUM WAS LOCATED AND OVERPACKED, AND SPILL INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP DRIVER WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DISPOSAL FACILITY.    PSC ENVIRONMENTAL ASSUMED RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE LEAKING CONTAINER AND PAID ALL INVOICES, AND FINES.
column169: PSC ENVIORNMENTAL PUT TOGETHER AN SOP FOR DRUM INSPECTION AND HANDLING.

column168: DRIVER LOST CONTROL NAVIGATING ROUNDABOUT INTERSECTION. TRACTOR AND TRAILER ROLLED ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE. THE TRAILER LANDED ON A CONCRETE CURB, CAUSING A CRACK IN THE VERY REAR, RIGHT CORNER OF THE REAR COMPARTMENT. RECIEVED CALL AT APPROX. 7:00 AM THAT THE ACCIDENT HAD OCCURED. THE OTTUMWA FIRE DEPT WAS ON SCENE WITH SPILL RESPONSE (HAZ MAT TEAM) CONTAINING SPILLED PRODUCT FROM REACHING ANY WATERWAYS.  WE HAD ANOTHER TRUCK AND TRAILER IN THE AREA AND WE PUMPED OVER REMAINING PRODUCT.  TEMPERATURES WERE VERY HOT AND WAS VERY SUNNY, THEREFORE PRODUCT EVAPORATED QUICKLY. CLEAN UP OF DIRT WAS DONE BY ROGER RENFREW. RESPONSE WAS BY OTTUMWA FIRE DEPT, OTTUMWA CITY POLICE, LA DOT, AND D.N.R. COPIES OF REPORT INFORMATION AND CONTACT INFORMATION ATTACHED.    MEDIA REPORTED SPILL OF 7800 GAL WHICH WAS INNACCURATE. ONLY 1000 GAL WAS LOST.
